defaultLord Stern described it as a ‘profound contradiction between climate change policy and the valuations of listed companies’.
default 
defaultIn this conte
defaultxt, the risks of an over-relianc
defaulte on fossil fuels is apparent, yet 
defaultone fifth of the FTSE100 is mining and oil and gas firms, accounting for approximately 30% of the total market capitalisation. Carbon Tracker research found that the LSE has reserves listed
default on it equivalent to around 10 times the UK CO
default2
default budget between now and 2050 to keep within 2°C of global warming.
default Additionally, most of these reserves are located overseas exposing investors to decision-making and political processes around high carbon as
defaultsets in which they have no say. For example, a third of coal listed in London is located in Australia, a market 
defaultwhich exports 90% of its coal, and 
defaultwhere a number of factors are combining to raise costs and make their assets increasingly uncompetitive globa
defaultlly.
defaultLondon is also the primary listing for a number of oil and gas majors. These corporations are increasingly reliant on oil
default which is 
defaulthard to get at because almost all the most easily extractable reserves have been exploited. Essentially this means they
default are producing less and less oil for 
defaultevery dollar
