defaultgs authority or the LSE to disclose or even consider climate change in its business strategy. 
defaultFor example, in Glencore’s 1,637-page prospectus for its initial public offering to list on the LSE, just a single paragraph noted climate risk – ‘regulation of g
defaultreenhouse gas emissions could also have a material adverse effect on the demand for Glencore’s products’.
default This 
defaultboilerplate statement gives investors no idea of how significant company management consider the risk to be.
defaultMarkets need not be 
defaultresistant 
defaultto ch
defaultange
default;
default in fact their success relies on moving
default with the times and respond
defaulting
default to new risks, like climate change. Mining companies coming to the AIM market, a sub-market of the LSE, are encouraged to seek a Competent Persons report to verify the existence of 
defaultf
defaultossil fuel 
defaultreserves. This needs to be extended to consider 
defaultthe impacts of 
defaultclimate risk 
defaultfor reserves levels and 
defaultbusiness models as increasing emissions constraints come in and scaled up to the full LSE. UK Business Secretary, Vince Cable, supports being a f
defaultirst-mover by stating recently that ‘London can teach other centres how it [corpor
defaultate governance] should be done’, but needs to reflect this in actions.
defaultLondon has historically set the standards for other markets to follow, which has given it a competitiv
defaulte advantage due to the extra reputational benefits of listing in London. Unless London maintains this position, it will find itself having to compete more with other exchanges that have not built up the same historic reputation.
defaultWhat is the impact of the idefaultndustry of the UK signing up to the EITI?defaultThe LSE’s recent action to join the Extractives Industry Transparency Initiative (EITI) takes important steps to 
defaultenhancing the exchange by 
defaultencouraging the disclosure
default of revenues from coal, oil and gas development.
default 
defaultThis reflects the requirements of the US Dodd Frank Act and EU Accountability requirements. It is also fitting, given the UK’s lead in establishing the EITI.
default 
defaultHowever revenue transparency only occupies a small part of what is required. 
defaultThe UK should take a
default similar leadership position on requiring climate risk disclosure, specifically with regards to the CO
default2
default potential of their fossil fuel reserves. This information would allow investors to track exposure to high-carbon assets themselves, and observe if this 
defaultwas increasing or decreasing over time. 
defaultOur research reveals the extent to which the LSE is exposed to over-valued and potentially worthless fossil fuel assets. Regula
defaulttion and listings rules 
defaultneed to
default 
defaultbe aligned with this threat
default 
defaultto
default maintain the UK’s position
default as a global standard-setter
default.
default 
defaultThe UK has le
defaultd with the Climate Change Act and setting carbon budgets; this needs to be transferred across to its oversight of London as a major global financial centre.
default 
defaultWithout having market wide information on the exposure 
defaultto this issue it will not be possible for 
defaultregulators or investors to understand the level of exposure in London. At present there is a risk that investors who track the market seeking diversification are in fact ending up with a concentration in fossil fue
defaultl based businesses.
defaultWhat is the competitive landscape for the extractive industries in the 21defaultstdefault Century and is it in the UK’s interest to remain a global centre for them? defaultThe landscape for the extractives industries going forward sees them having to adapt
default to a low-carbon energy future or be comprehensively uncompetitive as their market shrinks. This transition may take time but the signals are apparent
default. Analysts at Deutsche Bank, Goldman Sachs and Citi see the first step is for coal to 
defaultbe a poor investment
default,
default primarily due to environmental regulations, China peaking its demand and market forces favouring cheaper gas.
defaultUnlike countries like Norway, the UK does not have vast sovereign wealth funds to finance sustainable energy infrastructure for future generatio
defaultns. Ins
defaulttead it will be the UK’s financial mark
defaultets that will need to adapt – enhanced regulation and requirements can guide this transition
default. For the UK to remain competitive going forward is needs to be getting 
defaultahead in the growth industries of a low carbon
default future. Otherwise this opportunity will be capitalised on elsewhere. 
